rComments: This class was a lot of work and not to be taken just for credits, you have to love the stuff and want it.  The professor was tough but fair,  available to help and with very high standards and little patience for laziness.

This was the hardest class that I have taken as an ecology major.  It really helps to record lectures, because Maggie talks fast with a lot of detail.  She knows EVERYTHING about vertebrates, so you learn a lot!  She's also nice and fairly humorous. The lab is also super hard but interesting! You learn fish, amphibs, reptiles, birds, and mammals.

Ugh, I hated this class.  Way too much memorization of pointless things.  Maggie is a good lecturer, and she will help you.  However, the class and lab were way too time consuming, and I had no time for my other classes, which got screwed over because of hers.

Great class.  Lectures revolve around the labs.  Two major papers and a final project.  Learn everything from how to make fiels maps to setting up field studys.  Maggie knows what she's talking about, and willing to work with everyone who wants to put the effort into the class.  Not for slackers, but definitely worth the time invovled!!

I really enjoyed this class.  It was a lot of work and we had to go on a "field trip" but I learned so much form this class.  I think Maggie is a great professor, she is very enthusiastic and knowledgable.

She's passionate but expects you to guess what she's thinking, or guess her right answer. Do it her way or you won't do well. Ask for help, ask questions. She is patient in explaining things, so take advantage of that. I like her enthusiasm and confidence.

The class was horribly disorganized and unreasonable. Maggie is very mothering, but usually in the worst way. I'd covered most of the material in a previous bio class, but it didn't help. Especially not recommended for ENVS majors.
Class sucked, everyone agrees. The end.
